---
import Primer from '../../layouts/Primer.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';
---
<Primer
  title="The Surface Beneath Everything"
  eyebrow="A Primer on Matter Models · Chapter One"
  deck="Before there is a model, there is a landscape. Two atoms and a dial reveal its shape. Mapping it is another matter."
  running="Ch. 1 — The Surface Beneath Everything"
  next={{ href: url('/primer/atoms-as-a-graph'), label: 'Atoms as a Graph' }}
>
  <p class="lead">
    Set one argon atom on a table and roll a second one toward it. Far apart, the two ignore each
    other. Bring them closer and they begin to pull together — gently, then harder. Closer still
    and the pull turns into a shove, because two atoms cannot share the same space. Somewhere
    between those extremes is a separation the pair settles into, the way a marble settles into a
    bowl.
  </p>

  <p>
    Give yourself two instruments. A <strong>dial</strong> that sets the distance between the atoms.
    A <strong>gauge</strong> that reads the energy of the pair at whatever distance you dial in.
    Turn the dial through every distance and write down the energy at each one. Plot it, and a curve
    appears: high on the left, where the atoms are crammed together; down into a valley at the
    settled separation; up to a plateau on the right, where the two stop noticing each other.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 300" role="img" aria-label="Energy of two atoms versus the distance between them: a steep wall when too close, a valley at the settled separation, a plateau when far apart.">
