        <line x1="120" y1="150" x2="120" y2="188" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1" marker-end="url(#a4b)" />
        <text x="120" y="212" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">one point</text>
        <circle cx="120" cy="234" r="4.5" fill="var(--ink)" />

        <line x1="210" y1="40" x2="210" y2="252" stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-width="0.75" stroke-dasharray="3 4" />

        <line x1="250" y1="36" x2="250" y2="252" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1" />
        <line x1="250" y1="252" x2="700" y2="252" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1" />
        <text x="244" y="48" text-anchor="end" class="svg-label">energy</text>
        <text x="698" y="272" text-anchor="end" class="svg-serif-it">arrangement</text>

        <path d="M 262 78 C 312 150, 350 178, 392 178 C 440 178, 486 104, 528 100 C 574 106, 626 168, 676 96"
              fill="none" stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="2" />
        <circle cx="288" cy="116" r="4" fill="var(--ink)" />
        <circle cx="360" cy="174" r="4" fill="var(--ink)" />
        <circle cx="430" cy="150" r="4" fill="var(--ink)" />
        <circle cx="500" cy="104" r="4" fill="var(--ink)" />
        <circle cx="560" cy="120" r="4" fill="var(--ink)" />
        <circle cx="640" cy="132" r="4" fill="var(--ink)" />
        <text x="470" y="234" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it">the fitted potential: evaluated anywhere, in milliseconds</text>

        <defs>
          <marker id="a4b" markerWidth="9" markerHeight="9" refX="7" refY="4.5" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L9 4.5 L0 9 z" fill="var(--ink)" /></marker>
        </defs>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 4</span>The escape. Each black dot is one arrangement someone paid for in DFT — a slow, trustworthy reading. The oxblood curve is the potential, fit to thread the dots. A few thousand readings; the potential fills in the rest.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Two things to carry forward. First, nearly every such model computes its forces as the exact
    slope of its own energy — the rule <em>F</em> = −∇<em>E</em> applied to the model itself, not a
    second quantity figured on the side. A model's energies and forces can never contradict each
    other, which matters the moment you step the atoms forward in time.
  </p>

  <p>
    Second, the accuracy — and here the calculator analogy breaks. We know the true sine on its own
    terms: we can compute it to any precision and check the formula against it at any angle, so its
    error is bounded everywhere and can always be made smaller. An MLIP has no such anchor. The
    surface it fits is the very thing too expensive to evaluate, so it cannot be checked everywhere.
    Near the arrangements it trained on, it is excellent. Far from them — an exotic bond, a pressure
    no training structure ever saw — it can be wrong, and it will not warn you. There is no precision
    dial; the remedy is to feed it more DFT where it is weak, and knowing where it is weak is its own
    hard problem.
  </p>

  <p>
    And even at its best, an MLIP cannot beat its teacher. It learned DFT, so it inherits DFT's
    mistakes: where the reference gets a bond wrong, the model gets it wrong too — confidently, and a
    million times faster. DFT is not reality, only a good approximation to it; the model is an
    approximation to that.
  </p>

  <p>
    And the electrons? Having done their work in the training data, they never appear in the
    finished model. Which leaves the word we have leaned on without earning it: <em>fit</em>. We keep
    saying the model is fit to the surface and built from local pieces — but how does a function take
    a list of atomic positions and hand back one energy, cheaply, while honoring that locality? That
    is where we turn next.
  </p>
</Primer>
